e8593a84-f5a7-4839-bbc3-163b4eaa47d9	ba589d35-c603-458f-b28d-15cebcece444	("(""(""""(""""""""(widget)"""""""",widget)"""",id)"",2415eb6d-c33d-46de-a008-cea1acf89cc2)","(""(""""(widget)"""",widget)"",html)")	<div id="{{= id }}" class="{{= name }}">\n    <h1>Documentation</h1>\n\n    <h2>Contents</h2>\n\n    <ul>\n        <li><a href="#intro">Introduction</a></li>\n        <li><a href="#architecture">Architecture Overview</a></li>\n        <li><a href="#dev">Development IDE</a></li>\n        <ul>\n            <li><a href="#datum">Datum API</a></li>\n            <li><a href="#widgets">Widgets</a></li>\n            <ul>\n                <li><a href="#widget_function">widget()</a></li>\n                <li><a href="#sync_function">widget.sync()</a></li>\n            </ul>\n            <li><a href="#debugger">The Debugger</a></li>\n        </ul>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h2><a name='intro'>Introduction</a></h2>\n\n    <p>Aquameta is a collaborative web application development and data sharing platform implemented entirely in PostgreSQL.  It's architecture is based on a first principle of <em>datafication</em>, where the programming stack is modelled as relational data.  All operations under the hood are manipulations of relational data.</p>\n\n\n    <h2><a name="architecture">Archicecture Overview</a></h2>\n\n    <p>Aquameta has seven architectural layers whcih together comprise a web development stack.</p>\n\n    <h3>1. meta - Writable System Catalog</h3>\n    <p>PostgreSQL features, modelled as relational data.  A collection of views which query the system catalog.  Triggers on the views enable PostgreSQL DDL operations through data manipulation.  A type system for each view that allows "soft" foreign key references to system components.</p>\n\n    <h3>2. semantics - Meta-metadata</h3>\n    <p>Express the semantic relationships between tables, set human identifiers, decorate columns and tables with their default display and edit widget, human name, semantic data type, etc.</p>\n\n    <h3>3. bundle - Data Versioning</h3>\n    <p>A  snapshotted version control system similar to git but for versioning rows in the database.</p>\n\n    <h3>4. event - Subscriptions-based</h3>\n    <p>Subscribe to notifications of data changes on tables.</p>\n\n    <h3>5. www - Resources, Data Manipulation API, Change events over http/ws</h3>\n    <p>Implemented as a <a href="http://www.postgresql.org/docs/9.4/static/bgworker.html">background worker</a>, www exposes PostgreSQL authentication, a data manipulation API, resource sharing and data events over HTTP and WebSocket.</p>\n\n    <h3>6. p2p - WebRTC Peer</h3>\n    <p>Implemented as a <a href="http://www.postgresql.org/docs/9.4/static/bgworker.html">background worker</a>, p2p enables direct peer-to-peer communication over NATs via the <a href="http://www.webrtc.org/">WebRTC</a> protocol.</p>\n\n    <h3>7. widget - Modular UI Components</h3>\n    <p>Enables composition of web applications in modular, reusable, self-contained components.  Each widget has functional inputs, templated html and css, and some javascript code.</p>\n\n    <h2><a name="ide">Development IDE</a></h2>\n\n    <p>A full stack development environment made of widgets, enabling PostgreSQL administration and application development.</p>\n\n    <h3><a name="datum">Datum API</a></h3>\n\n    <p>endpoint.schema('airport').table('flights').rows() returns a Promise.</p>\n\n\n\n    <h3><a name='widgets'>Widgets</a></h3>\n\n    <p>A widget is a modular user interface component, composed of some HTML, CSS and Javascript.  Widgets can have inputs, dependencies, documentation, database views, and more.  They should generally be able to stand alone as a complete, self-contained component.  Some widgets can be designed to be general purpose, reusable across multiple projects.  Others are specific to just one project.</p>\n\n    <h3><a name="widget_function">widget(name, inputs)</a></h3>\n\n    <p>Loads a widget by name, passing in inputs and returning an element that can be inserted into the DOM.</p>\n\n    <p>Args:</p>\n\n    <ul>\n        <li><b>name</b>: A string matching a row's name field in the widget table.</li>\n        <li><b>inputs</b>: An object to be passed into the widget, and accessible from the widget's css and html templates, pre_js and post_js.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <p>Example:</p>\n\n    <pre>\nvar element = widget('ascii_planet', { \n   \tcolor: 'white', \n    click_handler: function (e) {\n        alert ('hello click');\n    }\n});\n    </pre>\n\n    <h4><a name='function_sync'>widget.sync (rows, container, widget_generator)</a></h3>\n    <p>Instantiates a bunch of widgets into the supplied container, one for each row in the supplied set of rows.</p>\n\n    <h5>Args:</h5>\n    <ul>\n        <li><b>rows</b>: A <a href="#datum_rowset">datum rowset</a> containing a set of rows.  Each row will be the argument to the widget_generator.</li>\n        <li><b>container</b>: A jQuery element which will be appended.</li>\n        <li><b>widget_generator</b>: A function which must return a call to widget.  This function is called once for each row in the supplied rowset.</li>\n    </ul>\n\n    <h5>Example:</h5>\n\n    <pre>\nvar boats = endpoint.schema('sailors').table('boats').rows();\n\nwidget.sync(\n    boats,\n    w.find('.boats_container'),\n    function(boat) {\n        return widget('boats_icon', { boat: boat });\n    }\n);\n\n</pre>\n    <h3><a name='debugger'>The Debugger</a></h3>\n\n    <p>Implemented as widgets, this interface enables PostgreSQL administration and application development.</p>\n\n\n    <p>The debugger is a widget that debugs other widgets.  It can be embedded on any page, and displays what widgets are on the page, what datums are being used, and allow the developer to click into and edit those widgets without leaving the page.  You can bring it up on any page that includes the 'debugger3_manager' widget, with ctrl+alt+x.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n</div>
